type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>erct-003S</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>By induction on <fr:tex>n</fr:tex>; the base cases for <fr:tex>n=-2</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>n=-1</fr:tex> are given by <fr:ref
addr="erct-002V"
href="erct-002V.xml"
taxon="Corollary"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="erct-0026"
href="erct-0026.xml"
taxon="Lemma"></fr:ref> respectively. In the inductive step, we assume that <fr:tex>s \colon  B \to  A</fr:tex> exhibits <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> as a <fr:link
href="erct-0025.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-0025">retract</fr:link> of <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> and that for each <fr:tex>x,y:A</fr:tex> the identification type <fr:tex>x=_Ay</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="erct-001G.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001G"><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n+1</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:link> to show that for all <fr:tex>u,v:B</fr:tex> the identification type <fr:tex>u=_Bv</fr:tex> is likewise <fr:link
href="erct-001G.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001G"><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n+1</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:link>. The result follows from our assumption and the fact that <fr:tex>u=_Bv</fr:tex> is (by <fr:ref
